<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written from Campaign to Protect Rural England (SRN 042)</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written from</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Campaign</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Protect</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Rural</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">England</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">(SRN 042)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">key</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">points</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The Campaign to Protect Rural England (CPRE) is concerned that the problem of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> new roads generat</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> traffic </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">is no longer acknowledged in the Government’s roads policy;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The c</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">laim that new roads </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">and ‘ultra-low emission vehicles’ </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">need not impact the environment ignores the critical issue of land take and is problematic in relation to carbon and noise;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We do not believe that o</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">fficial forecasts are credible and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">they </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">can never be until the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">impact of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> taxation </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">and charging of road users on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> traffic levels is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">explicit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The aspirations in Action for Roads are being let down by outdated guidance and a rushed, poorly </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">thought </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">out Route Based Strategy process</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> with insufficient data</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Adopt a range of demand management measures, in particular tolled High Occupancy Vehicle lanes and packages to influence travel behaviour</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, to lock in the benefits of the recent decline of traffic as well as any increases in capacity;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Promote the use of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the best practice European road designs (cable-stayed </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">2+1 roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> as a safe and more sustainable alternative to land hungry dual carriageways;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Ensure </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">that the draft </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">National Networks National Policy Statement supports modal shift from road to rail and sets out scenarios rather than forecasts for both modes;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Significantly update the Design Manual for Roads and Bridges, National Transport Model, and Route Based Strategy process and ensure application of open data principles to each of them</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> to facilitate ease of use;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Require </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">integration of strategic planning for </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">different </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">forms of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">transport</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and tie this in with land use planning</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, such as by better guidance on</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> duty to co-operate;</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Build in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">range of environment and social goals into balanced regulation </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">performance specification for Highways Agency</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> – this should include a watchdog or regulation system that represents those negatively impacted by roads as well as</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> road users</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">welcome</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">opportunity</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">submit</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Transport</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Committee</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">inquiry on the Strategic Road Network.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">As</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">leading</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">environmental</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">charity,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Campaign</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Protect</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Rural</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">(CPRE)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">has</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">worked</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">promote</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">protect</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">beauty,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">tranquillity</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">diversity</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">rural</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">England</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">since</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">1926.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> We have been involved in roads policy since the 1930s.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> desire to tackle a perceived 'infrastructure deficit' </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">and to help</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the UK to compete better in 'the global race'</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> is based on a statistic quoted in Action for Roads. But this figure that  that</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> UK is ranked by the World Economic Forum as having only the 24</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> best roads in the world</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> was </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">based on a single survey question asked of 93 top executives</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. It has distracted policy makers from previously gathered evidence showing the problems with road-building.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> In a crowded island, we will never be able to build enough road capacity to have roads as uncongested as less sparsely populated countries. Besides improved maintenance and better alternatives, the main improvement needed is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">management of demand. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the environment?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">If Department for Transport (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">) forecasts are correct, the additional capacity provided would only reduce the rate of predicted increases in congestion – rather than actually reduce it – albeit at a devastating cost to the environment. The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> has acknowledged to CPRE that its forecasts do not take into account any generation of traffic by the additional capacity it is proposing. The Roads Command Paper</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> in 2008 acknowledged that 'benefits delivered by new capacity in terms of reliable journey times can be quickly eroded [and] traffic levels can increase by up to 8–10 per cent every year'. With new capacity in congested areas inducing so much additional traffic, the benefits on the Strategic Road Network (SRN) are likely to be even less.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Almost all journeys start and end on the local road network and where new capacity induces so much traffic, local roads seize up even more. Many businesses say that the first and final parts of journeys are the most unreliable but the economic and environmental cost of expanding these roads increases exponentially. Probably the biggest weakness in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> was the failure to acknowledge that increasing capacity on the SRN would simply move bottlenecks onto local roads. Demand management is needed to 'lock in' any benefits of additional capacity but demand management would actually reduce the need for that capacity in the first place. With infrastructure expansion being on trend, demand management is, however, seen by officials as harking back to the 1990s.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Environment</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">In terms of vehicles, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> claims that 'ultra-low emission vehicles could eliminate much of the environmental damage from car travel’ (paragraph 1.19). There are a number of problems with this argument: even in relation to battery electric vehicles, at high speeds, noise levels are similar to conventional cars. In urban areas such as central London, the majority of particulate emissions now </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">comes</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> from tyre and brake wear rather than the exhaust pipe. Even in relation to carbon emissions, there is the problem of the rebound effect – dealt with below in relation to forecasting – but decarbonisation is particularly challenging for longer-distance journeys and freight, which of course are disproportionately on the SRN.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">In terms of the infrastructure, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> claims '[</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">]</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">mprovements</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> in materials and design, together with new methods to mitigate and minimise the environmental impacts of roads, mean that there no longer has to be a choice between a well-functioning road network and a well-protected environment.' (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">paragraph</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> 3.6). This view ignores the issue of land take for road-building, whether of farming land or precious habitats such as ancient woodland. It is worth comparing HS2, which would use electric trains, would be narrower than a dual-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">carriageway, not have night time traffic and includes much more tunnelling than all roads built in the last century put together. Nonetheless there is still significant opposition to it.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Design standards</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.75pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">A further challenge to improving the environmental performance of roads is the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Design Manual for Streets and Bridges (DMRB), key parts of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">which </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">dates from 1992</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, the year </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Twyford</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Down was destroyed for the M3 extension and the high point of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Roads for Prosperity</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> programme. If, as has been claimed, modern standards for road-building have improved in recent years, the DMRB has not been updated to reflect this. Yet it is this practical guidance that has rather more impact on scheme design than high level strategy documents. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The DMRB is based on paper updates to a loose leaf binder and has become cumbersome and bloated in size. This is a very outdated approach that does not allow for </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">hyperlinking</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> cross-references in the on-line version. Just as planning guidance has been slimmed down and made web-based, a similar radical approach is needed for DMRB. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Expressways</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.75pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> takes a wrong turn with its proposals to upgrade 'a large proportion' (paragraph 2.7) of the SRN to dual carriageway standard</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> so as to ensure free-flowing traffic. Yet even some</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> of the hotspots, for example the A1 north of Newcastle and the A303</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> highlighted in paragraph 2.8 in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> will not </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">experienc</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> congestion in 2040</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, at least according to the accompanying maps</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. This policy </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">goes way beyond the discredited 'predict and provide'. As </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">report</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> CPRE issued </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">jointly</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> this summer showed</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">this would resurrect many of the most damaging roads and threaten a dozen nationally designated landscapes. Even in ordinary countryside, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">dualling</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> would require very significant land take, particularly with current practice to build offline rather than simply adding an additional two lanes.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.75pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Nonetheless, as an organisation that has challenged the Government to improve safety on rural roads, on which over two-thirds of road deaths occur, CPRE cannot ignore the poor safety record of rural single carriageways. Similarly the frustrations felt by people living in rural areas when they are regularly stuck behind slow moving vehicles. On the continent the concept of ‘expressways’ is common, with motorway features but between two and four lanes in total. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> however proposes that all expressways should always be dual carriageways, even in nationally protected landscapes, but fails to consider the need for a separate signage regime. With the biggest refresh in a generation of the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Traffic Signs Regulations and General Directions due in 2015, it risks misses the boat.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.75pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We believe that</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the 2+1 road, which has </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">overtaking lanes that alternate sides and have a cable-stayed barrier in between</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, could be an alternative solution</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Developed in Sweden as part of its </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Vision Zero </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">for road safety, these can have the same safety record as motorways at 110km/h (68mph) yet their cross section has almost two-thirds less land take than a dual carriageway (13m rather than 21.1m, excluding verges) while providing for three-quarters of the capacity</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. Other countries such as the Republic of Ireland have adopted them successfully but again the UK is let down by its outdated highway standards. Although there is guidance in DMRB on 2+1 roads (TD 70/08), this pre-dates the use of central cable-stayed barriers, which makes them </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">much</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> safe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. CPRE believes that 2+1 roads not dual carriageways should be the standard for expressways.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Non-motorised users (NMUs)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 0.75pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The risks faced by NMUs trying to travel across or along trunk roads are high: the risk of death of cycling along a rural </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> road is 15 times higher than cycling on average. Rights of Way often cross these roads at grade and in many instances they </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the only direct route available for miles. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> poses the question rather than any answers, saying simply ‘[t]</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">he Highways Agency will need to think strategically about how it can best support non-motorised traffic, to stop the network being a barrier for walkers and cyclists.' (</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">paragraph</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> 3.33). It is telling that while there is a commitment for the standard of expressways for drivers, there is nothing specific about the minimum level of provision for NMUs. The commitment to ‘cycle-proof’ the network is vague and a better approach would be to plan for high levels of modal shift to cycling </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">before</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> considering where additional capacity for motor traffic might be needed.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Route Based Strategies (RBSs)</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The RBS process has only just begun but is already proving disappointing</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and the timetable is so tight that it may prove difficult to improve matters significantly</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">CPRE lobbied for a commitment to retrofitting existing roads to bring them up to modern environmental standards – whether through adding noise barriers, extra landscaping or NMU provision - so welcomed a commitment to do this in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.  The Agency is only considering the environmental impact of new road proposals however and has recently acknowledged CPRE’s concerns that this falls short of Government policy. The mapping used by the Agency for the RBSs is extremely poor</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, taking an approach that is </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">unchanged in a decade. CPRE has suggested adapting </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> innovative</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> approach to mapping</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">used at </span><a href="http://www.hs2maps.com"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.hs2maps.com</span></a><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">,</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">which</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> uses a range of open data, such as from Natural England and the 2011 Census, to put </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">needs and </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">impacts into context </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">so as to</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> help prioritise issues for RBSs.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Although there is a commitment for post 2019 roads investment to be considered alongside Control Period 6 for rail, this seems sufficiently far off for integration not to be considered now. The maps and materials produced for Route Based Strategies do not, for example, include the rail network let alone potential for coaches or barriers to non-motorised transport. Despite </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> making the right noises in relation to integration, in practice it is difficult to envisage how the link with other modes could be worse.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">It would be wrong to place all the blame solely with the Highways Agency. During the consultation on Network Rail’s Long Term Planning Process, CPRE highlighted that the potential to increase rail capacity where road capacity faced greater environmental constraints had not been identified. Rather than </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">dualling</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the A303 through the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Blackdown</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Hills A</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">rea of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">O</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">utstanding </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">N</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">atural </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">B</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">eauty</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, for example, the two under-used railway lines running parallel either side could be upgraded together with safety improvements to the road itself. The National Networks National Policy Statement (NNNPS), which is now due to be consulted on by the end of this year, should provide an opportunity to consider such issues and CPRE looks forward to this Committee’s consideration of it.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">While </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> mentions maintenance, greater freedom for local authorities as well as other Departmental initiatives such as the Door-to-Door strategy, it misses out any policy to fill the gap in strategic planning created by the abolition of the regional tier, other than a few anecdotes about City Deals and the A30. The ‘duty to co-operate’ that was introduced by the Localism Act 2011 is a very limited procedural duty and CPRE raised </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">concerns in its recent response to consultation on the draft Planning Practice Guidance (PPG)</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">This is not just about joining up different forms of transport, it needs joining up of transport and land use. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> raises concerns that </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Enterprise Zones, potential housing sites and areas of high growth will be held back by bottleneck conditions’ (paragraph 1.25). But if these developments occur in the wrong place, they will sow the seeds of bottlenecks in future. The need to ‘plan more to travel less’ was explicitly left out of the PPG </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">and CPRE is concerned that Strategic Economic Plans will be drawn up in the dark of this critical issue. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">CPRE’s joint report </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">with the Campaign for Better Transport</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> on Local Transport Bodies</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> (LTBs)</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> highlighted how only 15% of schemes identified with major developments that LTBs were prioritising are for sustainable travel modes.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> In addition, it is notable that LTBs are not currently subject to the duty to co-operate.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How reliable is the Government’s forecast for growth in demand for the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The forecasts are not credible in the short-term – in that they represent a radical change to trends seen over the last decade – nor in the long-term – as the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> accepts huge uncertainty about the propulsion system of vehicles (hence cost of use) after 2030.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> This could have different impacts on different types of journey as, for example, electric vehicles are less suited to longer journeys. </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The phrasing of this question suggests that traffic levels cannot be influenced, like the weather. Far from it, the main driver of the forecasts is a reduction in the cost of driving due to greater fuel efficiency. This leads to a further problem, known as the rebound effect, where people </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">react to the decrease in the cost of driving by </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">driv</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ing more</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">. The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> has modelled that the result would mean that carbon emissions from vehicles would be </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">greater</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> in 2030 than they are now.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Despite the Government’s cycling ambition announced in summer 2013, the forecasts assume no increase in the cycling rate, nor any use of rail capacity freed on existing congested lines by HS2. The </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> acknowledges that </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">‘[t]he biggest urban areas, particularly London, are seeing very different trends from the rest of the country’ that</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> its National Transport Model</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> (NTM)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> has failed to predict. But the roll out of smart-ticketing, cycling measures and demand management policies could mean that more areas buck the predictions.</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> The NTM is a closed-model and the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> has refused to disclose to CPRE information about the development of its modelling. This is contrary to the spirit of open government.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">With technological and other uncertainty increasing, CPRE has argued for a scenario approach to be used in relation to the appraisal of HS2 instead of forecasts. We believe a similar approach should be applied to the SRN. This is likely to be resisted officially as the Government may feel it will be easier to attract private investment if it can pretend it can be relatively certain about future traffic levels. We believe it imperative that the NNNPS adopts a scenario approach rather than definitive traffic forecasts.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new technology have?</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Capacity and reliability can be increased by making traffic more homogeneous, whether in terms of reducing speed differentials between vehicles or journey types – short-distance traffic that junction hops conflicts with long distance traffic. Reducing variability in turn reduces the risk of collisions or other perturbations. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Besides increasing capacity measures to increase the average number of people travelling or amount of goods per vehicle also increase efficiency. Utilisation of much of our road network is very inefficient, with many cars carrying just one person and freight vehicles lightly loaded. Although new technologies can reduce the distance between vehicles, they are likely to be less useful for shorter journeys such as around congested urban areas. Demand management measures are therefore critical, such as:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">High Occupancy Vehicle (HOV) Lanes  - these can encourage lift sharing </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">while</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> mak</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> additional coach services commercially viable</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, there should be a presumption that all lanes opened by Hard Shoulder Running should be HOV lanes</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Influencing Travel Behaviour programmes – lauded in the 2011 Local Transport White Paper for a Benefit Cost Ratio as high as 13:1, though the Highways Agency having withdrawn all funding for them months earlier;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Road user charging</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the German truck toll has reduced empty running but the equivalent being introduced into the UK is not sophisticated enough to do this. </span></li></ul><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">As noted in the previous answer, new technology could dramatically reduce the cost of driving, particularly for shorter journeys. Unless new forms of demand management were introduced, this could significantly increase traffic growth around major urban areas, significantly increasing congestion.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The Government proposes very significant spending on the SRN and rail but there is a growing gulf in respects of how these investment programmes are to be funded. In respect of rail, passengers continue to face fares increasing above the rate of inflation. For the SRN, however, not only has the rate of fuel duty been frozen, effectively meaning a cut in real terms of income from users, but also EU fuel efficiency targets mean that the price paid per distance travelled will decrease by as much as 30% over this decade as engines require less fuel. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Even if the Government had not announced the biggest investment in roads in a generation, this situation would be as unjust as it is financially and fiscally unsustainable; the case for a national road user charging scheme, however controversial, grows stronger over time. There are problems with the alternatives:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Hypothecating fuel tax would mean a declining income stream over time;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">A fixed annual charge for use of the SRN would mean those who used it a few times per year would pay the same as those who used it a few times a week;</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Tolling roads means limited usage, where an existing route remains available, (e.g. M6 toll), or a real risk of rat-running on unsuitable minor rural roads where the existing route is clos</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ed (e.g. A14 in Cambridgeshire).</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Short of a national road user charging scheme, which would need to be designed very carefully</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, one option successfully used in other countries is the option of paying to use a </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">HOV</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> lane. This gives people a choice of not paying and staying in the slow lane as well as the ability to use the lane if they lift share. By giving an advantage to coach services, it would also help attract private investment for additional services, which would be more beneficial than investment in additional infrastructure.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Action for Roads</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> makes a fair case for reform of the Agency but, compared to the Cook Review, proposes changes that would mean the Agency focuses on motorists as its customers. This would effectively leave out of consideration communities and the natural environment, despite them facing negative impacts from the road network. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 2.25pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 1.5pt; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The National Planning Policy Framework highlights the importance of economic, social and environmental goals being sought ‘jointly and simultaneously’. We suggest a similar approach should be built into the core of a reformed Agency through:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Primary statutory purpose</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> of the Agency being defined in the roads reform bill to be to deliver sustainable development and more efficient use of its network;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Powers for the Secretary of State to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">draw up detailed guidance on environmental and social goals</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> of the Agency and a commitment in Parliament to engage with NGOs etc. in drawing this guidance up;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">P</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">erformance Specification</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> including much broader metrics than the 2013-2015 version and extensive use of open data to ensure variation in local performance is not masked by national trends;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Watchdog or regulator</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> to ensure representation of interests of those indirectly affected by the SRN as well as direct users.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:11pt">7</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Paragraph</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">5.26 in </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Roads: Delivering Choice and Reliability </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, 2008)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> For example DMRB </span><a href="http://www.dft.gov.uk/ha/standards/dmrb/vol10/section1.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Volume 10 Environmental Design and Management</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.bettertransport.org.uk/media/15-july-NGO-roads-map"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Charities warn National Parks under threat from Highways Agency dual carriageways</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, 2013</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.vti.se/en/publications/evaluation-of-21-roads-with-cable-barrier/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">Evaluation of 2+1 roads with cable barriers</span></a><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, (Swedish National Road and Transport Research Institute, 2009)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p styl